Stock Assessment

The provision of fisheries management advice requires

  • The assessment of stock status relative to reference points,
  • The prediction of the response of a stock to management, and
  • Checking that the predictions are consistent with reality.

Prediction skill

Prediction skill

An Operating Model is a mathematical siumulation model used to project forward. OMs are commonly conditioned using a stock assessment model on historical data, however, in MSE the focus is on the future not the past.

The major uncertainty in stock assessment models is the difference between models and reality. Validation of predictions are difficult for fish stocks, however, without draining oceans.

  • Hindcasting and model-free validation can be used to evaluate multiple measures of prediction skill.
  • In a hindcast a model is fitted to the first part of a time series and then projected over the period omitted in the original fit.
  • Prediction skill can then be evaluated by comparing predictions from a projection with future observations observations.

Hindcast

Stock assessments use a variety of data types and sets, and statistical stock assessment models have been developed as an attempt to integrate multiple diverse datasets in order to extract as much information as possible

  • Datasets are often conflicting and scenarios that reflect a range of hypotheses need to be developed and scenarios to be weighted or rejected.
  • Can not use AIC to compare models when datasets change

Hindcast

Objectives

Evaluate the prediction skill of scenarios, using a range of data types, assessment models, i.e. biomass, size based, age based, integrated and state space.

  • Indentify the main uncertainies for including in OMs.
  • Use multiple measures to help understand the error structure of signals to construct Observation Error Models.
  • Identify datasets with the best signal to noise ratio for use in Management Procedures
